  sodium: 1893 mg
time required: 40 minutes
servings: 2
---

1 olive oil
1 cauliflower
1 bag green beans
1 bag baby spinach leaves
1 packet beef mince
½ packet fine breadcrumbs
1 egg
30 g butter
2.5 tbs milk
¼ tsp salt
¼ cup water
½ sachet Chicken-Style Stock Powder
1 sachet All-American Spice Blend
1 packet Shredded Cheddar Cheese
1 packet BBQ sauce
½ packet Dijon mustard
1 bag parsley
1 potato

Bring a medium saucepan of salted water to the
boil. Peel the potato and cut into large chunks.
Cut the cauliflower into small florets. Trim the
green beans.

In a medium bowl, combine the beef mince,
fine breadcrumbs (see ingredients), All-American
spice blend and egg. Using damp hands, roll
heaped spoonfuls of the beef mixture into small
meatballs. Transfer to a plate. You should get 4-5
meatballs per person. In a large frying pan, heat a
generous drizzle of olive oil over a medium-high
heat. Cook the meatballs, turning, until browned
and cooked through, 8-10 minutes (cook in
batches if your pan is getting crowded). Transfer to
a plate.

TIP: Don't worry if the meatballs char a little, this
adds to the flavour!

While the meatballs are cooking, cook the potato
and cauliflower in the boiling water until easily
pierced with a knife, 10-15 minutes. In the last
5 minutes of cook time, add the green beans to
a colander or steamer basket and place on top
of the saucepan. Cover with a lid and steam until
tender. Transfer the beans to a bowl, then add the
baby spinach leaves. Drizzle with a little olive oil,
season with salt and pepper and cover to keep
warm. Drain the potato and cauliflower, then
return to the saucepan.

Add the butter, milk and the salt to the saucepan
of potato and cauliflower, then mash until
smooth. Stir through the shredded Cheddar
cheese. Set aside.

Return the frying pan to a low heat. Add the water,
BBQ sauce, Dijon mustard (see ingredients) and
chicken-style stock powder (see ingredients). Stir
until well combined and simmer until thickened
slightly, 2-3 minutes. Return the meatballs to the
pan and toss to coat in the sauce.

TIP: Add a dash more water if the sauce gets
too thick.

Roughly chop the parsley leaves. Divide the cheesy
mash, smokey BBQ beef meatballs and steamed
greens between plates. Spoon over any remaining
BBQ glaze. Garnish with the parsley to serve.